    <!-- Health Articles Section -->
    <section id="articles" class="py-5 searchable-section">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="text-center mb-5">
                <h2 class="fw-bold text-primary"><i class="bi bi-journal-medical me-2"></i>Verified Health Articles</h2>
                <p class="text-muted">Updated for 2026. Sourced exclusively from authorized medical professionals and institutions.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="row g-4" id="articles-container">
                <!-- Card 1 -->
                <div class="col-md-6 search-item">
                    <div class="card h-100 shadow-sm border-0 border-top border-primary border-4">
                        <div class="card-body">
                            <span class="badge bg-secondary mb-2">Infectious Diseases</span>
                            <h4 class="card-title fw-bold text-dark-blue">Preventing Dengue in Communities</h4>
                            <p class="card-text text-muted">With shifting climate patterns in 2026, dengue remains a year-round threat in the Philippines. The DOH emphasizes the "Enhanced 4S Strategy": Search and destroy breeding sites, Secure self-protection, Seek early consultation, and Support fogging in hotspot areas.</p>
                            <blockquote class="blockquote blockquote-custom fs-7 mt-3 p-2 bg-light border-start border-3 border-info">
                                <p class="mb-1 small">"Eliminating stagnant water sources is the single most effective way to curb Aedes aegypti vector reproduction near residences."</p>
                                <footer class="blockquote-footer ts-small mt-1">Approved by <cite title="Source Title">Dr. Edsel Salvana, DOH Technical Advisory Group</cite></footer>
                            </blockquote>
                        </div>
                        <div class="card-footer bg-transparent text-muted small border-0 pt-0 ps-3 pb-3">
                            <strong>Source:</strong> Department of Health (DOH) Philippines | <strong>Published:</strong> January 2026
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Card 2 -->
                <div class="col-md-6 search-item">
                    <div class="card h-100 shadow-sm border-0 border-top border-primary border-4">
                        <div class="card-body">
                            <span class="badge bg-secondary mb-2">Cardiovascular Health</span>
                            <h4 class="card-title fw-bold text-dark-blue">Hypertension and Lifestyle Interventions</h4>
                            <p class="card-text text-muted">High blood pressure silent-kills millions. Mayo Clinic research highlights that restricting sodium intake to under 2,300 mg daily, tracking a DASH diet high in whole grains, and performing 150 minutes of weekly aerobic exercise drastically reduces stroke vulnerabilities.</p>
                            <blockquote class="blockquote blockquote-custom fs-7 mt-3 p-2 bg-light border-start border-3 border-info">
                                <p class="mb-1 small">"Small, consistent drops in sodium intake combined with brisk walking can drop systolic BP by 5 to 8 mm Hg."</p>
                                <footer class="blockquote-footer ts-small mt-1">Approved by <cite title="Source Title">Dr. Sheldon G. Sheps, Mayo Clinic Cardiology</cite></footer>
                            </blockquote>
                        </div>
                        <div class="card-footer bg-transparent text-muted small border-0 pt-0 ps-3 pb-3">
                            <strong>Source:</strong> Mayo Clinic Medicine | <strong>Published:</strong> March 2026
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Emergency First Aid Section -->
    <section id="firstaid" class="py-5 bg-light searchable-section">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="text-center mb-5">
                <h2 class="fw-bold text-danger"><i class="bi bi-heart-pulse me-2"></i>Emergency First Aid Protocols</h2>
                <p class="text-muted">Standard life-saving procedures verified by the Philippine Red Cross and CDC. Read carefully.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="row g-3">
                <div class="col-12 search-item">
                    <div class="p-4 bg-white rounded border shadow-sm">
                        <h4 class="fw-bold text-danger"><i class="bi bi-activity me-2"></i>1. Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation (CPR)</h4>
                        <p class="mb-2"><strong>Indication:</strong> Unresponsive individual who is not breathing or only gasping.</p>
                        <ol class="small text-muted mb-0">
                            <li>Call emergency services (911) immediately.</li>
                            <li>Place hands in the center of the person's chest and push hard and fast (100–120 compressions per minute).</li>
                            <li>Allow chest to return to normal position between compressions. Minimize interruptions.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="col-12 search-item">
                    <div class="p-4 bg-white rounded border shadow-sm">
                        <h4 class="fw-bold text-danger"><i class="bi bi-person-fill-exclamation me-2"></i>2. Choking (Heimlich Maneuver)</h4>
                        <p class="mb-2"><strong>Indication:</strong> Person cannot speak, cough, or breathe due to airway obstruction.</p>
                        <ol class="small text-muted mb-0">
                            <li>Stand behind the person. Wrap arms around their waist.</li>
                            <li>Make a fist with one hand. Place it slightly above the navel.</li>
                            <li>Grasp the fist with your other hand. Press hard into the abdomen with a quick, upward thrust.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="col-12 search-item">
                    <div class="p-4 bg-white rounded border shadow-sm">
                        <h4 class="fw-bold text-danger"><i class="bi bi-fire me-2"></i>3. Burns (Thermal Burns)</h4>
                        <p class="mb-2"><strong>Indication:</strong> Red, blistered, or painful skin from heat exposure.</p>
                        <ol class="small text-muted mb-0">
                            <li>Cool the burn under cool (not freezing) running water for at least 10 minutes.</li>
                            <li>Do not apply ice, butter, or oil to the burn—this traps heat and causes tissue damage.</li>
                            <li>Cover loosely with a sterile, non-stick bandage.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="col-12 search-item">
                    <div class="p-4 bg-white rounded border shadow-sm">
                        <h4 class="fw-bold text-danger"><i class="bi bi-droplet-half me-2"></i>4. Severe Bleeding</h4>
                        <p class="mb-2"><strong>Indication:</strong> Profuse, continuous blood loss from a wound.</p>
                        <ol class="small text-muted mb-0">
                            <li>Apply direct pressure on the wound with a sterile cloth or clean gauze.</li>
                            <li>Maintain continuous pressure until bleeding ceases. Elevate the wounded limb above heart level if possible.</li>
                            <li>Do not remove the blood-soaked cloth; stack new cloths on top if blood seeps through.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="col-12 search-item">
                    <div class="p-4 bg-white rounded border shadow-sm">
                        <h4 class="fw-bold text-danger"><i class="bi bi-bandaid me-2"></i>5. Fractures & Bone Injuries</h4>
                        <p class="mb-2"><strong>Indication:</strong> Deformed limb, extreme pain, or inability to move a body part post-impact.</p>
                        <ol class="small text-muted mb-0">
                            <li>Do not try to realign or push back a bone that is sticking out.</li>
                            <li>Immobilize the area using a splint (rolled newspapers, wooden boards) tied gently above and below the injury.</li>
                            <li>Apply a cold pack wrapped in a cloth to reduce swelling.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="col-12 search-item">
                    <div class="p-4 bg-white rounded border shadow-sm">
                        <h4 class="fw-bold text-danger"><i class="bi bi-brain me-2"></i>6. Stroke (Recognize F.A.S.T.)</h4>
                        <p class="mb-2"><strong>Indication:</strong> Sudden neurological deficit due to compromised cerebral blood flow.</p>
                        <ul class="small text-muted list-unstyled mb-0">
                            <li><strong>F - Face:</strong> Ask the person to smile. Does one side of the face droop?</li>
                            <li><strong>A - Arms:</strong> Ask them to raise both arms. Does one arm drift downward?</li>
                            <li><strong>S - Speech:</strong> Ask them to repeat a simple phrase. Is speech slurred or strange?</li>
                            <li><strong>T - Time:</strong> If any sign matches, call 911 immediately. Every minute matters.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="col-12 search-item">
                    <div class="p-4 bg-white rounded border shadow-sm">
                        <h4 class="fw-bold text-danger"><i class="bi bi-heart-break-fill me-2"></i>7. Heart Attack</h4>
                        <p class="mb-2"><strong>Indication:</strong> Crushing chest pain radiating to the left arm or jaw, sweating, shortness of breath.</p>
                        <ol class="small text-muted mb-0">
                            <li>Have the individual sit down, rest, and try to remain calm.</li>
                            <li>Loosen any tight clothing around the neck and waist.</li>
                            <li>Administer emergency aspirin if recommended by medical dispatchers over the phone while waiting for help.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

