    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section id="faq" class="py-5 bg-light">
        <div class="container" style="max-width: 800px;">
            <div class="text-center mb-5">
                <h2 class="fw-bold text-primary">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
                <p class="text-muted">Quick medical answers based on institutional reference manuals.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion shadow-sm" id="faqAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <h2 class="accordion-header">
                        <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faq1">
                            Is a fever dangerous by itself?
                        </button>
                    </h2>
                    <div id="faq1" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion">
                        <div class="accordion-body">
                            According to Johns Hopkins Medicine, a fever is not an illness itself but a natural response showing the body is fighting off an infection. It only becomes critical if it crosses 103°F (39.4°C) in adults or remains sustained across multiple days.
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <h2 class="accordion-header">
                        <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faq2">
                            When should a stroke patient be brought to a hospital?
                        </button>
                    </h2>
                    <div id="faq2" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion">
                        <div class="accordion-body">
                            Immediately. The CDC notes that thrombolytic medications (clot-busters) must ideally be administered within 3 to 4.5 hours from the first onset of stroke signs to mitigate long-term brain damage.
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

